<exercise checkit-seed="0008" checkit-slug="L1" checkit-title="The Logic of English Statements">
    <statement>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>Write down two English sentences. The first should be a logical statement, and the second should not be a logical statement. Explain why the one is a statement and the other is not.</li>
                <li>Consider the statement "everybody is laid back and I have a healthy diet". If "everybody is laid back" is False and "I have a healthy diet" is False, what is the truth value of the statement? Justify your answer using the definitions of the basic logic words.</li>
                <li>In English, write the negation of the following quantified statement: "no octopuses are small." </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>Recall that a logical statement has to be either true or false. Commands and questions are examples of English sentences which are not statements.</li>
                <li>The statement is False.</li>
                <li>The negation is "some octopuses are small."</li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </answer>
</exercise>
